tive geographic terms.  In the Medicine Wheel, upon which Anishnabe culture is based, I see embodied spirituality and many aspects of nature but nothing that remotely suggests physical location as an important element of that culture.  Perhaps that is because the location and extent of present-day Sault tribal lands, indeed the lands of most native american tribes, have been dictated by a white settlers' government that selected and allotted them to suit their own needs and wishes.  You certainly do not have to go back to the days of Newfoundland or Nova Scotia habitation but only to the mid 19th century to see that the Anishnabe occupied a much larger area of the Great Lakes region than the Upper Peninsula service area which now encompasses only about 1600 acres.  <br>
<br>
But even if an argument can be made on cultural grounds for the return of members to the service area, tribal life is more than just culture, it is economics as well.  And economic conditions within the service area are not bright.  In 1999, the Bureau of Indian Affairs (BIA) reported a 71 percent unemployment rate among tribal members with 22 percent of those employed living below the poverty level.  Those statistics probably are not too surprising given that the economy of the eastern Upper Peninsula of Michigan is largely tourist-driven.   And the absence of a strong year-round economic base probably was what drove many Chippewa tribesmen away to the cities during the last 100 years in search of ways to support themselves and their families.  These brave people took with them the values and precepts of the Anishnabe and, if my family can be used as an example, passed them on to their offspring.  While these later generations have few if any ties to the artificially constructed seven-county service area, many do embrace the culture at least as strongly as some who live there.  And we do not &quot;play&quot; our identity, we live it through our strong connections with those caring persons who inculcated within us that identity and who have since walked on.  So in one respect you were absolutely correct; Anishnabe is a culture based on blood ties. Many of us also choose to mix with and interact with other tribes thereby learning of other native cultures and enhancing our own.   Here is an interesting question; what effect would there be on the Sault Tribe economy if the 20,000 plus members living &quot;below the bridge&quot; perceived a need to more closely embrace their culture and moved en masse to the service area?<br>
<br>
Like you, many who live outside the service area expect no financial or material rewards from the Tribe.  However, given the fact that now the Tribal economy is of a size that would be the envy of many small third-world countries, the outside voices demand to be heard.  This seems to be a reasonable expectation, if for no other reason than financial contributions to the Tribe by the U.S government are based on total membership size and not just on the number of members living in the service area. As it appears that those outside voices are largely ignored under the present organizational structure, it is entirely reasonable and appropriate to establish direct representation through at-large seats.<br>
<br>
Now Egoboy let me apologize, to you and to others who may read it, for the length of this communication.  And let me assure you that I am not trying to get you to agree with me; your previous communications make it obvious that such an accomplishment would be impossible given my limited powers of persuasion.  However, I do hope that others will read this interchange and make up their own minds.  With that I rest my case.<br>
<br>
Charles E. Adams, Jr (actual name)<br>
